I n August 2014, the militarization of U.S. police departments was on public display as police ofﬁcers who were dressed like soldiers used military-style equipment and armored vehicles to confront protestors in Ferguson, Missouri. Following the shooting death of a black teenager by a white Ferguson police ofﬁcer, the Ferguson city and St. Louis County police employed military-style tactics to confront large protests, both peaceful and violent, that emerged in the area of the shooting. The police tactics emphasized the use of Special Weapons and Tactics (SWAT) teams in military-style uniforms and body armor to confront protestors and even involved the deployment of snipers atop armored vehicles. This militarized response by local police was thoroughly documented

by local, national, and international media and drew criticism from numerous commenters and public ofﬁcials (Shesgreen 2014).
Much of the public’s interest in the events in Ferguson was grounded in the well-worn and historically familiar racial dimensions of the shooting, particularly the relations between a black public and a white police force. The police response was also a stark visual reminder, however, of the militarization of civilian law enforcement agencies (LEAs) in the United States, many of which have used federal programs to acquire surplus military equipment, including weapons, armored vehicles, and body armor. This article explores the geographies and histories of one the most important equipment acquisition programs, called

