1033, to better contextualize an important element of the phenomena of U.S. police militarization. Our goal is to provide a historicized and spatialized understanding of the 1033 program that situates events like the response to the Ferguson protests as localized expressions of a larger and more systematic process.
We begin by discussing how geographers have examined the topic of policing before introducing a theory of police and the state and the notion of police militarization. Next we describe the 1033 program, emphasizing its history and legal rationales to clarify the connections between the program and the war on drugs. We then explore the geographic extents of 1033 at the county level using data from the Department of Defense, ﬁnding that the overall usage of the program has increased dramatically in recent years, that there is a great deal of spatial variability in the utilization of the program by LEAs, and that the usage of the program is not just restricted to large counties with paramilitary SWAT-style policing units. Our concluding discussion emphasizes the implications of our ﬁndings for future research and why sustained geographic inquiry is essential to understanding the varied processes of police militarization.
Geographies of Policing
Geographers have long noted the centrality of notions of place, territory, and space to policing (Yarwood 2007). For instance, many of the everyday activities of the police emphasize the need for ofﬁcers to have a detailed and nuanced understanding of the places and people they are tasked with managing (Fyfe 1991; Yarwood and Paasche 2015), whereas formalized police patrol beats are spaces of law enforcement used to organize, partition, and manage policing efforts (Paasche, Yarwood, and Sidaway 2014), reﬂecting the use of territory to inﬂuence or control social interactions (Sack 1983). Further, many of the tactics that police use to manage affairs within their beats are inherently spatial, such as dispersing people from a particular location, creating checkpoints to limit movement, or relocating individuals through detention or arrest (Herbert 1996b, 1997; Crank 2015). In sum, place knowledge, territoriality, and the spatial management of people are important ways in which social order within places is made geographic.
Geographers have also explored the “thin blue line” police subculture that celebrates the role of police in preserving social order (Balko 2013). Police culture is often described as exhibiting a highly masculinist ethos that prizes the use of force while embracing a deep suspicion of the public (Fyfe 1991; Herbert 1998) and has been represented as a key way to understand the everyday actions of police (Crank 2015). Because places are an important mediator of social life, geographers have also drawn attention to the variability of police culture. For instance, Fyfe (1991) compared policing approaches at the national scale, concluding that police subculture is not monolithic and should be

expected to vary geographically. Similarly, Herbert (1998) argued that elements of police culture vary institutionally, which serves as a geographic insight as policing in the United States is highly decentralized and localized (Klinger 2004).
As a contextual explanation of police behavior, Fyfe (1992) claimed that police culture alone might receive too much attention from researchers and that other contexts are also important inﬂuences on and mediators of policing. For example, the rise of neoliberal governance has shifted some aspects of policing toward a myriad set of private companies (Paasche, Yarwood, and Sidaway 2014) while also emphasizing the responsibility of individuals to police their own spaces through voluntary programs like neighborhood watch (England 2008). Neoliberalism has also been connected to the deployment of zero-tolerance policing policies in particular spaces within cities in support of businesses and commerce (Mountz and Curran 2009) or through police efforts to clear some urban neighborhoods of homeless people in support of gentriﬁcation (Smith 2002). An important challenge for geographers is to therefore connect how such larger scale contexts affect the everyday practices of policing within places.
Considering the legal limitations on police power provides an important example of why such larger contexts matter. For instance, police in the United States are legally constrained from entering private property without permission or probable cause, which affects the conduct of police during calls to private residences (Herbert 1996a). Laws that locate some spaces as beyond the reach of police power illustrate how the immediate contexts of policing are themselves partly constituted by larger scale processes. The nationalscale legal structures that clearly delimit police power are also important elements of the everyday decisions and actions of the police and are present in their interactions with the policed. Such large-scale inﬂuences, whether de jure or de facto, should be seen as therefore vitally important contextual elements for understanding how policing works within particular places.
It is important to note that despite the preceding discussion, relatively little work on policing has been published by geographers. Perhaps apart from the notable exception of the collected work of Herbert, Fyfe’s (1991) call for more engagement by geographers was largely ignored; Yarwood’s (2007) similar call seems to have had the same limited impact to date. Although it is not clear why the topic continues to have such a small footprint within geography, we speculate that the difﬁculties of conducting data-driven research, qualitative or quantitative, with such a notoriously closed group might be part of the story. In any event, we agree with both Fyfe (1991) and Yarwood (2007) that the topic has great potential for geographers simply given the salience of power and space to policing.
Police and the State
This rather small literature by geographers on police has tended to focus on the everyday activities of police

