ofﬁcers within speciﬁc institutional–geographic contexts, such as Herbert’s (1996a, 1996b) studies of the Los Angeles Police Department. In some ways, this emphasis has reﬂected a larger trend in the study of police beyond geography, which emphasizes the institution of “the police” that is tasked with responding to crime and enforcing the law. Much of this literature takes the police for granted by focusing on the tasks, strategies, and actions of policing institutions without clearly articulating a broader sense of what police are. Other efforts to theorize police have focused on the power of police to order social life (e.g., Neocleous 2006, 2014), which has led to a consideration of policing as a form of state power.
Approaching police through the lens of the state was largely inspired by Foucault’s notion of governmentality (Dubber and Valverde 2006). For example, Foucault (2007) traced the history of the idea of police in Europe and argued that it refers to the “means by which the state’s forces can be increased while preserving the state in good order” (313). Following this argument, the police could be said to be part of a broader technology of governance and crucial to the everyday functioning of the state. Although this perspective suggests that the aspects of social life that might be policed are wide and varied, Neocleous (2006) anchored the idea of policing in class terms: Within modern states, “the police mandate was to fabricate an order of wage labor and administer the class of poverty thereafter” (21). Evidence for the relationship between the police and economic practices of the state can be found in examples as diverse as the tax collection responsibilities of sheriffs in Norman-era England (Williams 2004) and the repeated examples of the use of police forces as strikebusters in the United States during the nineteenth and twentieth centuries (Spitzer and Scull 1977; Walker 1977).
Although such a theory of police is largely compatible with the geographic perspectives on police activity described earlier, these theories are also partial as they tend to evoke and reinforce the classic domestic–foreign spatiality of the state. Police are then typically described in this literature as concerned with social order within “the interior of the state” (Foucault 2007, 327). However, the spatiality of police and the state is more complex than this simple binary for at least two interrelated reasons. First, the development of formal institutions of policing within individual states was, in some cases, grounded in extraterritorial politics. A prime example is found in the introduction of the ﬁrst uniformed police force in London in the late 1820s (the so-called Peelers), which was itself was modeled on the experience of enforcing British colonial rule in Ireland (Williams 2004). As such, the introduction of a new means to provide domestic order within the space of the state was partly “informed by the experience of colonial rule” (Williams 2004, 35). That the experiences of colonial control could affect the practices of policing disrupts the simple territorial binary found in most policing theory and is evocative of Foucault’s

(1997) observation that dominating other societies had implications for the colonizer at home as “the West could practice something resembling . . . an internal colonialism, on itself” (103).
The second challenge to the binary spatiality of police and the state is that historically the scale of policing activity tends to be very localized, creating a highly differential set of motives, tasks, and contexts within which policing occurs (Dubber and Valverde 2006). This can be seen in the differences between “slave patrol” police forces in the U.S. South and the early modern urban police departments in many northern U.S. cities (Harring 1983). Slave patrols, ﬁrst introduced into Southern colonies as early as the mid1600s, were ofﬁcial efforts to catch runaway slaves, prevent slave gatherings, “and generally intimidate the Black population” (Williams 2004, 40). Although the details varied among the colonies with such patrols, the motives and logics of this form of policing centered on maintaining the status quo of slavery. In contrast, the uniformed urban police forces introduced in the 1840s and 1850s were focused not on the needs of the system of slavery but on those of the local political machines of the era. As Fogelson (1977) wrote, the goal of these police forces was rarely about keeping order in the streets; and violence between social groups was actually often tolerated as a means to “keep competing groups in their place” (19). Instead, police were largely concerned with “preserving order at the polls” to ensure that their political patrons won reelection (Fogelson 1977).
We generally accept the Foucault-inspired approach to police as part of the state as well as Neocleous’s understanding of police as concerned with the maintenance of the economic status quo. We also assert that theorizing police and as part of the state necessarily involves a complex set of scales and geographies that includes the local, the national, and, perhaps at times, the international as well. Certain sites will also be important to the realization of police power at speciﬁc moments in time (country backroads, urban polling places, picket lines, the colony), but these sites will vary among a set of states as well as within any given state. In addition, a close connection of police to the needs of the state implies that other aspects of state power need to be considered as well.
Police and the Military
State-centered theories of policing have led some to reﬂect on the connections between police and another potent form of state power, the military. Enloe (1980) remarked that together the police and the military represent the legal use of a state’s coercive force, and Turk (1982) explicitly linked the two by arguing that police are a means of producing social order within the territory of a state without resorting to the use of direct military control. Although these perspectives are largely drawn from modern examples of policing,

