Kraska and Kappeler (1997) described what they call the close connections between police and the military historically and politically in the United States. These connections are found from the earliest days of police forces in the United States in the adoption of uniforms and military-style ranks. Further, the use of a military analogy that framed crime and disorder as a “war” was among the chief strategies used by a police reform movement in the early twentieth century to break the hold of local politicians and the political machines over what was seen as a set of corrupt local police institutions. Fogelson (1977) described this strategy as tapping into a “widespread admiration for the navy and army” at the time by emphasizing the “integrity, efﬁciency, and dignity of the military” (57) and that this reform effort led to a more militarized police in the United States.
The use of the war analogy by the police in producing and maintaining social order has been repeated many times since (Simon 2007) and is ultimately grounded in an underlying philosophy or ideology of militarism in which the threat or use of force to resolve social or political issues is seen as normal, unproblematic, and efﬁcient; militarization then refers to the myriad ways in which the ideology is put into practice within a society (Enloe 2004). Both ideas are of growing importance for geographers and have been recently linked to a diverse set of issues in the United States such as the production of citizenship (Bernazzoli and Flint 2010), urban design (Graham 2010), environmentalism (Lunstrum 2014), health care (Loyd 2009), and migration (Silvey 2006). Militarism and militarization is an important lens for such diverse issues because of the trend toward “securitizing” social problems by framing them as threats to be attacked and overcome (Bernazzoli and Flint 2009a). These ideas have obvious utility for policing as the repeated use of the war metaphor toward social problems like crime or drugs frames them as emergencies requiring urgent martial solutions (Kraska 2001).
Although militarization takes on many forms, Bernazzoli and Flint (2009b) noted that it works similarly to Gramsci’s (1971) notion of cultural hegemony, which claims that the poorest members of society tended to adopt the values and norms of wealthy elites to explain why the working classes often act against their own economic self-interest. Bernazzoli and Flint argued that the processes of militarization work similar to cultural hegemony as the ideology of militarism is widely accepted even by those who might not beneﬁt from such an understanding, especially when the military has an elevated status within a society. Despite the pervasiveness of the ideology of militarism, it is important to note that processes of militarization are always realized within places and therefore should be expected to be, as Woodward (2005) pointed out, “temporally and spatially contingent” (720). Accordingly, militarism could be understood as an important yet often overlooked element of place construction, and militarization should be expected to present an

uneven spatial expression as the adoption of the ideology of militarism and the speciﬁc within-place practices inspired by it might vary widely.
The well-documented reliance on war metaphors (war on crime, war on drugs) by police and the historical reliance on force to produce social order led Kraska (2007) to argue that policing is a self-evidently militarized part of the state. As a consequence, research should be focused on the extent of its militarization rather than its existence. Along these lines, the rise of specialized paramilitary units in large urban police forces, such as the well-known SWAT teams in the United States, has been identiﬁed as an important contemporary indicator of the extent of police militarization (Kraska and Kappeler 1997; see also Herzog 2001). Although the historical origins of SWAT teams are typically described as a response to speciﬁc instances where police found themselves underequipped or “outgunned” (Balko 2013), these units often have direct connections to the military by hiring veterans with military training. SWAT teams have been critiqued as a direct threat to civil liberties and public safety due to the growth in their overall number and in their increasing use in everyday policing (American Civil Liberties Union 2014).
SWAT teams have comprised the focus of the limited research on police militarization to date (den Heyer 2014). For example, Meeks (2006) contended that the use of SWAT teams in urban policing strategies unevenly targets the urban poor and people of color in selective prosecution of a “war on crime,” and Falcone, Wells, and Weisheit (2002) argued that rural or small-town departments without SWAT-style units are on the right side of the trend as the introduction of SWAT-style units in these settings undermines trust between the police and the public. Although these and other critiques of SWAT teams (see also Hill and Beger 2009) differ in many ways, they agree that their use is (or should be) a point of concern. A limitation of this emphasis on SWAT teams and their adoption of military-style equipment and tactics is that it is ﬁxated on the obvious visible or material connections between policing and the military, such as those observed during the Ferguson protests.
Despite their importance to policing and to the public perception of the police, the presence or absence of these paramilitary units should not constitute the extent of police militarization as a police force can be militarized by other actions or practices even if it is without a SWAT unit. For example, the Latah County (Idaho) Sheriff, which serves a jurisdiction of roughly 38,000 people spread across 1,000 square miles in northern Idaho, has no SWAT team or specialized paramilitary unit but did acquire a military armored vehicle in 2014 (see Figure 1; Harber 2014). Even without the direct military connections that are often present with SWAT teams (Kraska 2007), military equipment and materials can still ﬂow to police departments in the United States in a variety of settings. A more comprehensive understanding of the processes of police militarization requires more than just a focus on SWAT trends

