The 1033 Program and the War on Drugs
The implications of the so-called war on drugs have been well documented by a wide range of scholars. For instance, the criminalization of drug use has been linked to rising incarceration rates in the United States and offered an as explanation for the racialized nature of the penal system that disproportionately affects people of color (e.g., Lynch 2012). Others have explored the political origins of the war on drugs (e.g., Simon 2007; Frydl 2013), its links to the neoliberal dismantling of the welfare state (e.g., Beckett 1997; Corva 2008), and its impacts in societies beyond the United States (e.g., Rincon-Ruiz and Kallis 2013). The connections between the drug war and aggressive policing, such as the type associated with SWAT teams, have also been well documented (Beckett 1997; Simon 2007; American Civil Liberties Union 2014). The drug war’s connections to other aspects of police militarization are less well known, however. The Department of Defense’s (DoD) 1033 program, which provides surplus military equipment at no direct cost to LEAs, was directly born out of the war on drugs and is a crucial driver of the material militarization of police.
Created by federal legislation in 1996, 1033 speciﬁes that military equipment may be transferred to LEAs to support antidrug efforts. The type of equipment available ranges from armored vehicles, personal protective equipment (helmets, vests, etc.), radios, ﬁrearms, and uniforms, to more mundane items like ofﬁce furniture, computers, televisions, and air conditioners. The types

and amounts of available equipment vary over time and LEAs can routinely browse 1033 inventories online. The DoD manages the 1033 program through the Law Enforcement Support Ofﬁce (LESO). The LESO Web site claims that it has distributed surplus military equipment valued at $4.3 billion since 1996 (Defense Logistics Agency 2015).
1033 draws its name from the section of the National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 1997 that made it permanent in 1996 (Pub. L. No. 104–201 1996). The program has deep legislative roots, however, and is the direct product of the U.S. military’s growing involvement in the drug war beginning in the 1980s. What would eventually become 1033 was ﬁrst introduced in a 1988 defense funding bill that rewrote signiﬁcant portions of federal law on the relationship between the military and local LEAs by specifying an active role for the military in antidrug efforts (Pub. L. No. 100–456 1988). The 1988 law itself was built on previous legislation passed in 1981 that allowed the military to provide temporary assistance in support law enforcement in drug interdiction, immigration control, or customs on a case-by-case basis (Pub. L. No. 97–86 1981; see also Hess 1990). Prior to the enactment of these two laws, the use of the military in matters of domestic law enforcement had been strictly prohibited by the Posse Comitatus Act of 1878.
The sum of these changes to the legal relationships between the military and police greatly increased the responsibilities of the DoD in prosecuting the drug war; the DoD was tasked with serving as the lead federal agency for “the detection and monitoring of aerial and maritime transit of illegal drugs into the United States” (Pub. L. 100–456 1988). As part of this newly legal mission, the DoD was also to make available to LEAs any equipment that was deemed necessary for them to carry out their drug interdiction efforts. A year later, Congress again expanded the military’s role in the drug war with the National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Years 1990 and 1991 (Pub. L. No. 101–189 1989), which formally created the 1033 program. 1033 was speciﬁed to expire in 1992 but was renewed periodically in defense spending bills until a 1996 defense spending bill (Pub. L. No. 104–201 1996) that made it a permanent feature of the legal relationship between the U.S. military and civilian LEAs.
The main rationale for this program in the 1980s was to ﬁght the drug war that had been part of federal policy since at least the late 1960s (Scott 2003; Frydl 2013).1 The issue of substance abuse and its collective impact on U.S. society was initially framed as a national security threat by political elites during the Vietnam War, as it was seen as a particular problem in prosecuting the war in Vietnam (Savage and Gabriel 1976). For example, heroin use by U.S. soldiers ﬁghting in the war was framed as “an epidemic” by President Richard Nixon in 1971 following a series of reports about the extent of heroin use in the U.S.

