Army (Baker 1971). Although there were other political motives for creating a new role for the federal government in law enforcement, such as race and political dissent (Beckett 1997), the drug issue was the center of a major policy effort by the Nixon Administration to provide new resources to local law enforcement to “stem the tide of drug abuse which has swept America in the last decade” (Nixon 1971).
The prosecution of the war in Vietnam and the aims of U.S. foreign policy at the time shed light on why the federal policies established by Nixon eventually culminated in a direct connection between the military and LEAs through the 1033 program. The perception that heroin addiction was undermining the war effort in Vietnam meant that the issue of drug use and abuse had risen from a matter of domestic law enforcement within U.S. cities to a national emergency that required new action at home and abroad. In part, this meant a shift away from a treatment-based approach to drug crimes and toward a militarized approach; U.S. borders and territory had to be secured against the ﬂow of heroin from abroad, which required military involvement. Although Nixon did not directly call for the program that ultimately became 1033, the seeds for such a move were planted decades ago (Beckett 1997; Simon 2007).
Geographies of 1033
Although 1033 has been in existence in some form since the late 1980s, the program has operated largely outside of public awareness or scrutiny. The DoD made partial records available to the public in late 2014, however, as part of a series of media stories that highlighted the existence of the program (e.g., Rezvani et al. 2014). These data covered 1033 activities from 2006 through early 2014 and were aggregated to the county where the equipment was sent. These data also contained detailed descriptions of the equipment, the date that the equipment was transferred, and an estimated value of the equipment. Following Kraska’s (2007) call to better understand the extents and trajectories of police militarization, we used these data to conduct an exploratory spatial analysis of the overall spacing and timing of acquisitions at the county scale from 2006 through the end of 2013.
During this eight-year period, more than 2,329,000 equipment transfers to LEAs were recorded (Table 1).2 Equipment was distributed to 80 percent of all U.S. counties and the number of transfers per county varied widely. Within counties that received equipment, transfers ranged from a low of 1 to a high of more than 177,000. In addition, equipment transfers were highly concentrated in just a few counties: Forty-two counties were recorded as the destination of more than 10,000 transfers during the eight-year time period and the ten counties with the most transfers accounted for 40 percent of the total (see Table 2). Although LEAs are able to request and acquire equipment at no direct cost, the estimated value of each item is recorded, which

provides an alternate measure of the program for analysis. The total value of all of the equipment transferred was over $1.5 billion (Table 1) with a lowest total value of $10 and a highest value of over $209 million. Similar to the transfers, just a handful of counties represented a signiﬁcant portion of the total value: Twentyﬁve counties received equipment valued at over $100 million during the time period and the ten counties with the highest cumulative values represented over 27 percent of the total value (Table 2).
All of the equipment in the data was identiﬁed using the U.S. government’s detailed Federal Supply Classiﬁcation (FSC) system, which consists of seventy-eight groups and 645 subclasses (see Defense Logistics Agency [2003] for a complete classiﬁcation list). Such detail was unnecessary for our analysis and we instead reclassiﬁed equipment into one of six broad categories (weapons, personal protective equipment, communication and surveillance, vehicles, armored vehicles, and miscellaneous) to simplify interpretation (see Table 3). Without regard to these categories, the annual value of transferred equipment increased from $34 million in 2006 to $530 million in 2013; the average annual increase in equipment value was 75 percent each year. The growth in the program, however, was largely due to increases in the transfers of vehicles (unarmored and armored) and of equipment that we assigned to the miscellaneous category (see Table 3 and Figure 2).3 These trends likely reﬂect the types of equipment that became available following the process of demobilizing U.S. forces from Iraq that began in late 2007.
As previously noted, the geography of 1033 equipment transfers was highly variable, with some counties receiving over $200 million in equipment and many others receiving none at all. Mapping both the summed value of equipment received by county and the summed value per capita using county population estimates from the 2010 census highlights two notable spatial patterns (see Figure 3). First, a large cluster of counties with low-value per capita acquisitions is present across several Great Plains states, with more localized lowvalue clusters present in Pennsylvania and Texas. Second, small clusters of high per capita acquisitions were found in the Southeast (notably in Tennessee and Alabama), the Southwest (Arizona, Colorado, and New Mexico), and the northern Rockies (Montana). Both observations were conﬁrmed with an exploratory test of local spatial autocorrelation and are suggestive that different processes might be at work both in different parts of the country and within states themselves (see Figure 4).
