through 1033, the events that occurred within Ferguson made 1033 and its usage by LEAs a highly visible and politicized issue. For example, the Obama Administration recently issued a report that recommended the restriction of certain types of military equipment to LEAs (White House 2015), and some state governments have advanced legislation to curb the usage of 1033.4 These efforts have in common a focus on visibly provocative equipment, such as grenade launchers, while overlooking the more mundane aspects of 1033, such as equipment with no clear connection to policing. The administration’s Law Enforcement Equipment Working Group recommended that the 1033 equipment lists “were expansive and included routine items such as ofﬁce equipment, cameras, and plywood” that have no particular law enforcement purpose (White House 2015, 11). Extending this logic to our ﬁndings is illustrative, as the bulk of the equipment acquisitions by LEAs are clearly not of the type emphasized by these policy reports and legislation (see Figure 2). Such policies then only tinker around the edges of the issue and do little to address the broad and increasing usage of the program across the United States.
Another important ﬁnding of our study is that the usage of the program, either taken as a whole or with regard to certain types of equipment, is highly spatially variable. Figure 3A shows high levels of 1033 usage in Southern California and Arizona, but that pattern is largely a function of population measures (Figure 3B). Controlling for population does suggest pockets of higher usage in southern states like Alabama and mountain states like Montana and the reasons for these patterns are likely to be more localized. For example, the relationships between race and policing might have more explanatory power in the South, the Southwest, or in diverse urban settings than in more homogenous rural counties. Kraska’s (2007) claim that police militarization is best understood as a continuum should be seen as necessarily having spatial contours;

