our ﬁndings are the ﬁrst indication of the location of some of the possible contours when it comes to issues of racial diversity.
The importance of local and regional contexts for 1033 usage is also reinforced with our ﬁndings of statistically signiﬁcant clusters of high and low acquisitions at the county scale. For instance, the groups of counties in Tennessee with similarly high 1033 equipment acquisitions (the red counties in Figure 4) are largely rural counties rather than those that encompass the major population centers in the state. It could be that there are shared contexts in those areas of the state that have led LEAs to make similar use of the program, but it is clear that these contexts are not geographically uniform. Somewhat differently, the group of high-usage counties in Alabama includes the Birmingham metro area and might reﬂect a shared perspective on the program among a group of interacting LEAs due to adjacent jurisdictions. In short, some of the clusters of high-usage counties might be the result of contexts that extend beyond the legal and spatial jurisdiction of a single LEA, but these are likely different within and between states. That is not to suggest that state-level policies on 1033 usage cannot be explanatory factors as well. For example, the large clusters of counties with similarly low 1033 usage (the blue counties in Figure 4) in Mississippi and Nebraska might indicate a strong oversight role being played by the state’s 1033 coordinator, a state-level administrative position required by the DoD.
Apart from the narrow focus on SWAT teams, however, Kraska and others provide little guidance as to why such variations are likely to exist and, crucially for

