geographers, where such highs and lows might be expected to occur. The variable regional histories of policing in the United States might be a helpful, although partial, lens on this issue (e.g., Williams 2004). A great deal of work remains for those interested in the processes that produce such variable outcomes, and the development of spatial data on the topic that can be used to test theory-driven hypotheses is an important next step. This will necessarily involve additional quantitative research using county-scale or smaller scale aggregated data to identify possible correlates to police militarization that might involve questions of racial or ethnic diversity, urban–rural differentiation, proximity to international boundaries and the perceived need to manage migrant ﬂows, policing of drug transportation corridors within the United States, or issues pertaining to the geography of incarceration.
In parallel with the type of research already described, place-speciﬁc research is also clearly needed to better illuminate the ties between LEA decision making about 1033 and the type of justiﬁcations used to advance or counter the program within particular places. In other words, given the new transparency of 1033 and the ongoing national scrutiny of police conduct, how are the issues connected to 1033 understood locally? A survey of the discourses surrounding 1033 in particular settings might be a particularly helpful ﬁrst step. For example, the Spokane (Washington) County Sheriff recently defended his agency’s acquisition of ﬁfty-seven M16 riﬂes through 1033 as necessary because law enforcement ofﬁcials are “on the ISIS hit list” (Henterly 2015, 17), and the Latah (Idaho) County Sheriff emphasized the need for an armored vehicle to respond to mass shooting events, one of which occurred in the county in 2007 (Harber 2014). These justiﬁcations rely on different scales (one with the global war on terror, the other with local events) but, tellingly, neither focuses on the drug war or how it has unfolded within those particular jurisdictions.

Following Fyfe (1991) and others, scholarship of this sort will necessarily involve qualitative inquiry about the unique local-scale impacts on LEA actions and justiﬁcations but should also consider how the larger scale processes of militarization, particularly those having to do with issues of foreign policy and national security, are mediated within particular places (Bernazzoli and Flint 2009b).
Finally, more historical geographic investigation is needed of the myriad legal structures and programs beyond 1033 that connect LEAs and the military. For instance, in addition to 1033, LEAs can acquire military-style equipment through programs run by the departments of Justice and Homeland Security (Rahall 2015). How have the laws connected to these sorts of programs changed over time and what are the associated spatial worldviews that underpin them? The justiﬁcation of the Spokane Sheriff is perhaps an obvious example in a possible shift away from antidrug and toward antiterrorism rationales in maintaining the ﬂow of military equipment to police, but there might be other relevant trends. Scholarship of this sort could also be fruitful in clarifying the role of race in police militarization. For instance, linkages between the geographies of the civil rights movement and the politics of gun control within particular places might also partially explain the varied landscape of police militarization in the United States.
We conclude by noting that our research is but a part of a larger set of questions regarding policing and the geography of socially constructed spaces of control that have emerged since the events of Ferguson in 2014. Although many of these questions have focused on the racial dynamics that have been implicated by the use of force by police ofﬁcers in speciﬁc cases, the kind of material militarization represented by 1033 is another window on the issue that can perhaps clarify a larger and crucial context that such individual cases are embedded within. Our research shows that the legal blurring of the police and the military that has enabled the spread of military equipment to LEAs has been ongoing for decades at the national scale, but this has resulted in an uneven landscape of police militarization at the county scale. Highlighting the presence of such spatial variability and ruling out simple global explanations for it, such as SWAT teams, opens a new range of questions including, but not limited to, those described earlier. Geographers then should be expected to play an important role in moving toward a more nuanced understanding of the trajectories, causes, and consequences of police militarization. &
